The start of the trial of the 29 men accused of the 2004 Madrid train bombings on Thursday stirred emotions for survivors and loved ones of the victims of the biggest terrorist attack in Spanish history.
A second alleged mastermind of the 2004 Madrid train bombings on Friday said he would only give evidence through his defence counsel.
Youssef Belhadj, the second of 29 suspects to appear before the Madrid train bombings trial, is believed to be "Abou Dujanah," a self-described Al-Qaeda spokesman in Europe, who appeared on a video found after the blasts claiming responsibility.
A timeline of the major events in the 2004 train bombings: --March 11, 2004: Ten backpack bombs explode on four commuter trains in Madrid, killing 191 and injuring more than 1,800.
